\pard\plain \tx1123\tx1685\tx2246\tx2794\tx3355\tx3917\tx4478\tx5040\tx5602\tx6163\tx6725\fi720\ri-720\sl288\slmult1\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Ayram led them to southeast leading Charnel road called the Hatthir road. There were plenty of pilgrim skeletons on the Hatthir road. One of them, it turned out, was still alive. Ayram noticed the man first. He picked up the poor pilgrim and set him the shade of a makeshift tent. The dying pilgrim stared out at all the Ayramun with winkless eyes. His skin was like paper, and his ribs were countable through the window in his yellow haircloth habit, while his stomach lay almost flat against his vertebral column.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 This pilgrim thought Ayram was Solraheen enfleshed. Ayram paused, sponged water onto the man\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s lips, and they made a brief, whispered exchange which Mandri could not hear.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Mandri gave the pilgrim one of Tob\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s rocks. It put a passing joy into the pilgrim\u8217\'92s eyes. Then the Ayramun moved on to let him die.}}